ch is to rid the body of fever. So the purpose of a war is to end the war.\n\n- William Faulkner, A Fable\n|\nYou cannot be afraid of the unknown. In every moment and with every step you take, the unknown becomes the known.\n\n- Dragos Bratasanu, Ph.D., Sleepers: A Little Book on How to Find Hope, Meaning and the Courage to Fall in Love with Your Dreams\n|\nIf each of us could help one orphan to build his/her capacity, and academic background rather than giving them money or food, then no family will sufferer without guardian.\n\n- Sbr\n|\nWe are metered only by our own machines,while the book is a clock that forgets her machanics.\n\n- Amy\n|\nI never made a mistake in my life; at least, never one that I couldn't explain away afterwards.\n\n- Rudyard Kipling, Under The Deodars\n|\nWho you are contributes to your poetry in a number of important ways, but you shouldn't identify with your poems so closely that when they are cut, you're the one that bleeds.\n\n- Dorianne Laux, The Poet's Companion: A Guide To The Pleasures Of Writing Poetry\n|\nI know many books which have bored their readers, but I know of none which has done real evil.\n\n- Voltaire\n|\nWhen we are aware of our weaknesses or negative tendencies, we open the opportunity to work on them.\n\n- Allan Lokos, Pocket Peace: Effective Practices for Enlightened Living\n|\nFire. God of Abraham, God of Isaac, God of Jacob, not of the philosophers and the scholars. I will not forget thy word. Amen.\n\n- Blaise\n|\nFor a bookworm like Mother, a Brontë novel sister was better than a biological one.\n\n- Eileen Favorite, The Heroines\n|\nDon't be such a party-pooper, missy --when you're well and truly screwed, either you just sit pissing yourself or you invent some reason to hope.\n\n- James Alan Gardner, Ascending\n|\nIt's not the face, but the expressions on it. It's not the voice, but what you say. It's not how you look in that body, but the thing you do with it. You are beautiful.\n\n- Stephenie Meyer, The Host